<div id="comment_65025123" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_65025123" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a rel="nofollow" id="comment_link_65025123" name="comment_link_65025123" href="//hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23555597&amp;cid=65025123" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(65025123)" >What has changed</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_65025123" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 65025123); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~laughingskeptic">laughingskeptic</a>  <span class="uid"><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~laughingskeptic">( 1004414 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_65025123"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_65025123">There are a lot of nay-sayers here.  I was a plasma physicist in the early 1980s -- a very disheartening time to be one.  Experimental plasma physics in this era was limited to phenomenology.  We simply did not have have the computational power to really understand what was going on.  It was not until 2015 that a plasma physics experimental device was fully modeled before construction.  This was the Max Planck Institute's Wendelstein 7-X which reached all of its design targets by 2022.  That is just 7 years</div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_65025123">

</div>
</div>

